<%# Phase 29 (settings refactor) — security pane (row 1 right).
    Phase 32 follow-up (2026-05-16) — 2FA / TOTP cleanup.
    Post-Phase-25 rollback — the auto-block list + locations modal
    launcher were removed along with the new-location approval
    surface.

    2026-05-16 (sessions revamp v2):

      * The "2FA: on / active sessions: N" helper copy + the
        "active sessions open in a modal." / "the direct link still
        works for JS-off clients." prose are gone — 2FA is mandatory
        (the gate forces enrollment), session counts and modal-vs-
        direct framing are noise.
      * The `[ sessions ]` modal launcher is gone. The sessions table
        renders INLINE inside this pane.
      * The `[ 2FA / TOTP ]` launcher was already dropped — the
        surface it opened (manage + disable + backup-code rotation)
        moved to operator rake tasks. 2FA enrollment itself is
        forced via the mandatory-2FA gate's auto-open modal on
        `/settings?enroll_totp=1`.

    2026-05-16 (sessions revamp v3 — modal-confirm):

      * The standalone `/settings/sessions/revokes/:ids` action-screen
        confirmation page is GONE. Bulk revoke now opens an in-page
        `<dialog>` confirm modal mounted at the bottom of this pane,
        following the same convention as the reindex modal in
        `_stack_pane.html.erb` (page-level mount keeps the CSRF token
        bound to the current session; `form_with` ensures the hidden
        `authenticity_token` is valid). The `sessions-bulk-revoke`
        Stimulus controller is extended to populate the modal's
        title text, conditional warning, and form `action` at click
        time — the modal is one shared instance, content is dynamic
        based on the current checkbox selection. %>
<div class="pane">
  <fieldset style="padding: 8px;" data-controller="sessions-bulk-revoke">
    <legend><h2>security</h2></legend>

    <% if @sessions.any? %>
      <%# Idle bulk-revoke toolbar — `[revoke]` muted/non-clickable
          until at least one checkbox is ticked. The
          `sessions-bulk-revoke` Stimulus controller mutates the
          anchor's text + classes in place as the selection changes.
          Clicking the live `[revoke N]` link opens the in-page
          `<dialog>` confirm modal mounted at the bottom of this
          pane (no navigation — the old action-screen page is gone). %>
      <div class="bulk-toolbar" style="margin-bottom: 6px;">
        <span class="action">
          <a data-sessions-bulk-revoke-target="link" class="bracketed-muted">[revoke]</a>
        </span>
      </div>

      <%# Tight table — mirrors the `/channels` density. Columns:
          checkbox / user-agent / pinged.

          2026-05-16 (sessions revamp v2 polish): the standalone `ip`
          column is gone. The IP value is now an inline
          `TooltipBadgeComponent` rendered at the END of the
          user-agent cell — `[ip]` reveals the address on hover.
          The current-row `(this session)` muted text is replaced by
          a `[this]` neutral status badge sitting after the `[ip]`
          badge. The `sessions.ip` database column is UNTOUCHED —
          only the rendered column is dropped.

          The `active` column was dropped earlier (the visible set is
          filtered to active-only) and the `remember` column was
          dropped along with the `sessions.remember` database column.
          Sortable headers drive `?sessions_sort=<key>&sessions_dir=
          <asc|desc>` on `/settings` itself. %>
      <table class="sessions-table" style="table-layout: auto;">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th class="col-action">
              <%= render(CheckboxComponent.new(data: { sessions_bulk_revoke_target: "headerCheckbox", action: "change->sessions-bulk-revoke#toggleAll" })) %>
            </th>
            <th class="sortable"><%= sort_link_to("user-agent", "user_agent", current_sort: @sessions_sort, current_dir: @sessions_dir, sort_param: "sessions_sort", dir_param: "sessions_dir") %></th>
            <th class="sortable num"><%= sort_link_to("pinged", "last_activity", current_sort: @sessions_sort, current_dir: @sessions_dir, sort_param: "sessions_sort", dir_param: "sessions_dir") %></th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <% @sessions.each do |s| %>
            <tr>
              <td class="col-action">
                <%= render(CheckboxComponent.new(
                  value: s.id,
                  data: {
                    sessions_bulk_revoke_target: "checkbox",
                    action: "change->sessions-bulk-revoke#toggle",
                    current: s.current? ? "yes" : "no"
                  }
                )) %>
              </td>
              <td style="max-width: 360px; white-space: normal;">
                <code><%= s.user_agent.presence || "—" %></code><%= render(TooltipBadgeComponent.new(label: "ip", tooltip: s.ip || "—")) %><% if s.current? %><%= render(StatusBadgeComponent.new(label: "this", kind: :success)) %><% end %>
              </td>
              <td class="num"><%= compact_time_ago(s.last_activity_at) %></td>
            </tr>
          <% end %>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    <% else %>
      <p class="text-muted" style="margin: 0;">no active sessions.</p>
    <% end %>

    <%# Revoke-sessions confirm modal (2026-05-16 revamp v3).

        One shared `<dialog>` mounted at the pane level. The
        `sessions-bulk-revoke` Stimulus controller populates the
        title (`revoke N session(s)?`), the conditional warning
        (`this set includes your current session. revoking it signs
        you out.`), and the form `action` attribute at click time
        based on the current checkbox selection.

        Page-level mount mirrors the reindex modal in
        `_stack_pane.html.erb` — the hidden `authenticity_token`
        baked by `form_with` is rendered in a real request context
        with a session-bound CSRF token, so submitting from the
        modal never trips `InvalidAuthenticityToken`. (A
        broadcast-driven render in a job context has no `request` /
        `session` and would bake an unbound token — same hazard
        called out in `_voyage_section.html.erb`.)

        The form `action` carries a literal `0` ids segment at render
        time (the route constraint `[0-9,]+` requires a digit, and
        `0` is filtered out by `parse_ids` server-side as a safety
        net — so a hand-crafted POST to the placeholder URL is a
        no-op). Stimulus rewrites the segment to
        `/settings/sessions/revokes/<real-ids>` when the modal opens.
        The hidden `confirm=yes` param mirrors what the deleted
        action-screen used to submit; `BulkRevokesController#create`
        still gates on it. %>
    <% if @sessions.any? %>
      <dialog id="revoke_sessions_modal" class="confirm-modal"
              data-controller="confirm-modal"
              data-action="click->confirm-modal#clickOutside keydown->confirm-modal#keydown"
              data-sessions-bulk-revoke-target="modal">
        <div class="confirm-modal-inner">
          <div class="dialog-title" data-sessions-bulk-revoke-target="modalTitle">revoke 0 sessions?</div>
          <div class="dialog-message" data-sessions-bulk-revoke-target="modalWarning" hidden>
            <p style="margin: 0;">this set includes your current session.</p>
            <p style="margin: 0;">revoking it signs you out.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="confirm-modal-actions modal-footer">
            <%# 2026-05-16 CSRF refresh — the hidden `authenticity_token`
                baked by `form_with` at page render is bound to the
                current session, BUT it can go stale if the session
                rotates between page render and confirm-click (TOTP
                gate completion, sign-in elsewhere in the tab, etc.).
                The `submit->sessions-bulk-revoke#refreshCsrf` action
                copies the current `<meta name="csrf-token">` value
                into the form's hidden token field immediately before
                the native POST fires — guarantees the request carries
                the page's freshest token regardless of why the baked
                value might be invalid. The handler does NOT
                `preventDefault()`; the native submit proceeds. %>
            <%= form_with url: settings_sessions_bulk_revoke_path(ids: "0"),
                          method: :post,
                          authenticity_token: true,
                          data: {
                            turbo: false,
                            sessions_bulk_revoke_target: "modalForm",
                            action: "submit->sessions-bulk-revoke#refreshCsrf"
                          },
                          html: { style: "display: inline;" } do %>
              <input type="hidden" name="confirm" value="yes">
              <button type="submit" class="bracketed text-danger">[<span class="bl">revoke</span>]</button>
            <% end %>
            <button type="button" class="bracketed" data-action="confirm-modal#close">[<span class="bl">cancel</span>]</button>
          </div>
        </div>
      </dialog>
    <% end %>
  </fieldset>
</div>
